2.4 Priority Matrix

Priority is derived from the intersection of severity and scope. This
matrix determines queue position in the defect backlog:

  ----------------- ----------------- ----------------- -----------------
  **Severity ↓ /    **Plan-Wide**     **Cohort**        **Individual**
  Scope →**                                             

  **Critical**      **P0 --- STOP**   **P0 --- STOP**   **P1 ---
                                                        Immediate**

  **High**          **P0 --- STOP**   **P1 ---          **P2 --- Urgent**
                                      Immediate**       

  **Medium**        **P1 ---          **P2 --- Urgent** **P3 ---
                    Immediate**                         Standard**

  **Low**           **P2 --- Urgent** **P3 ---          **P4 ---
                                      Standard**        Backlog**
  ----------------- ----------------- ----------------- -----------------

> *P0 --- STOP means all processing of affected case types halts
> immediately. No benefits are paid, no determinations are made for
> affected members until the defect is resolved and verified. This is
> the pension equivalent of a production outage.*

3\. Change Types and Review Gates

Not all changes carry equal risk. The design review process calibrates
its rigor to the fiduciary weight of each change type. Every change to
the NoUI system is classified into one of five types, each with a
defined review gate.

